{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778432671335,"sessionID":"ses_1ed2e5abdffeV49GJQcR5nFb98","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_nBiYQbQqnf3NADgWtDpQspJc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_15045140.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_15045140.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:15045140\n3: title: \"Extracellular fibrinogen binding protein, Efb, from Staphylococcus aureus binds to platelets and inhibits platelet aggregation.\"\n4: authors:\n5: - Shannon O\n6: - Flock JI\n7: journal: Thromb Haemost\n8: year: '2004'\n9: doi: 10.1160/TH03-05-0287\n10: keywords:\n11: - \"Bacterial Proteins/metabolism, pharmacology\"\n12: - Binding Sites\n13: - \"Blood Platelets/drug effects, metabolism\"\n14: - Fibrinogen/metabolism\n15: - Glutathione\n16: - Humans\n17: - Platelet Aggregation/drug effects\n18: - Platelet Glycoprotein GPIIb-IIIa Complex/metabolism\n19: - Protein Binding\n20: - \"Receptors, Virus/metabolism\"\n21: - Recombinant Fusion Proteins\n22: - \"Staphylococcus aureus/chemistry, pathogenicity\"\n23: content_type: abstract_only\n24: ---\n25: \n26: # Extracellular fibrinogen binding protein, Efb, from Staphylococcus aureus binds to platelets and inhibits platelet aggregation.\n27: **Authors:** Shannon O, Flock JI\n28: **Journal:** Thromb Haemost (2004)\n29: **DOI:** [10.1160/TH03-05-0287](https://doi.org/10.1160/TH03-05-0287)\n30: \n31: ## Content\n32: \n33: 1. Thromb Haemost. 2004 Apr;91(4):779-89. doi: 10.1160/TH03-05-0287.\n34: \n35: Extracellular fibrinogen binding protein, Efb, from Staphylococcus aureus binds \n36: to platelets and inhibits platelet aggregation.\n37: \n38: Shannon O(1), Flock JI.\n39: \n40: Author information:\n41: (1)Division of Clinical bacteriology, Department of Laboratory Medicine, \n42: Huddinge University Hospital F82, Karolinska Institute, S-141 86 Stockholm, \n43: Sweden.\n44: \n45: S. aureus produces and secretes a protein, extracellular fibrinogen binding \n46: protein (Efb), which contributes to virulence in wound infection. We have shown \n47: here that Efb is a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation. Efb can bind \n48: specifically to platelets by two mechanisms; 1) to fibrinogen naturally bound to \n49: the surface of activated platelets and 2) also directly to a surface localized \n50: component on the platelets. This latter binding of Efb is independent of \n51: fibrinogen. The specific binding of Efb to the putative receptor on the platelet \n52: surface results in a stimulated, non-functional binding of fibrinogen in a dose \n53: dependent manner, distinct from natural binding of fibrinogen to platelets. The \n54: natural binding of fibrinogen to GPIIb/IIIa on activated platelets could be \n55: blocked by a monoclonal antibody against this integrin, whereas the Efb-mediated \n56: fibrinogen binding could not be blocked. The enhanced Efb-dependent fibrinogen \n57: binding to platelets is of a nature that does not promote aggregation of the \n58: platelets; instead it inhibits aggregation. The anti-thrombotic action of Efb \n59: may explain the effect of Efb on wound healing, which is delayed in the presence \n60: of Efb.\n61: \n62: DOI: 10.1160/TH03-05-0287\n63: PMID: 15045140 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 63 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:15045140\ntitle: \"Extracellular fibrinogen binding protein, Efb, from Staphylococcus aureus binds to platelets and inhibits platelet aggregation.\"\nauthors:\n- Shannon O\n- Flock JI\njournal: Thromb Haemost\nyear: '2004'\ndoi: 10.1160/TH03-05-0287\nkeywords:\n- \"Bacterial Proteins/metabolism, pharmacology\"\n- Binding Sites\n- \"Blood Platelets/drug effects, metabolism\"\n- Fibrinogen/metabolism\n- Glutathione\n- Humans\n- Platelet Aggregation/drug effects\n- Platelet Glycoprotein GPIIb-IIIa Complex/metabolism\n- Protein Binding\n- \"Receptors, Virus/metabolism\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_15045140.md","time":{"start":1778432671323,"end":1778432671333}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_084689fc13ca7c64016a00ba9f212881a1ba4fb7cfb10e3e72"}},"id":"prt_e12d8fe49001pReYqCGFvHkE8V","sessionID":"ses_1ed2e5abdffeV49GJQcR5nFb98","messageID":"msg_e12d8efa50011CqFZOZvkbZgrB"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778432671357,"sessionID":"ses_1ed2e5abdffeV49GJQcR5nFb98","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_tlIvHG0Yh1ODlIM1RY19bp0b","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_15922770.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_15922770.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:15922770\n3: title: Jararhagin and its multiple effects on hemostasis.\n4: authors:\n5: - Laing GD\n6: - Moura-da-Silva AM\n7: journal: Toxicon\n8: year: '2005'\n9: doi: 10.1016/j.toxicon.2005.02.013\n10: keywords:\n11: - Animals\n12: - Antibodies/metabolism\n13: - Apoptosis/drug effects\n14: - Bothrops\n15: - Cell Adhesion/drug effects\n16: - Collagen/metabolism\n17: - \"Crotalid Venoms/metabolism, toxicity\"\n18: - \"Endothelium, Vascular/drug effects\"\n19: - Fibrinogen/metabolism\n20: - \"Hemostasis/drug effects, physiology\"\n21: - Inflammation/chemically induced\n22: - \"Metalloendopeptidases/metabolism, toxicity\"\n23: - Platelet Adhesiveness/drug effects\n24: - alpha-Macroglobulins/metabolism\n25: - von Willebrand Factor/metabolism\n26: - Bothrops jararaca Venom\n27: content_type: abstract_only\n28: ---\n29: \n30: # Jararhagin and its multiple effects on hemostasis.\n31: **Authors:** Laing GD, Moura-da-Silva AM\n32: **Journal:** Toxicon (2005)\n33: **DOI:** [10.1016/j.toxicon.2005.02.013](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.toxicon.2005.02.013)\n34: \n35: ## Content\n36: \n37: 1. Toxicon. 2005 Jun 15;45(8):987-96. doi: 10.1016/j.toxicon.2005.02.013. Epub\n38: 2005  Apr 2.\n39: \n40: Jararhagin and its multiple effects on hemostasis.\n41: \n42: Laing GD(1), Moura-da-Silva AM.\n43: \n44: Author information:\n45: (1)Alistair Reid Venom Research Unit, Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine, \n46: Pembroke Place, Liverpool, UK.\n47: \n48: Jararhagin is a 52 kDa hemorrhagic P-III metalloproteinase isolated from the \n49: venom of the medically important Brazilian pit-viper Bothrops jararaca. It is a \n50: member of the reprolysin family of zinc metalloproteinases containing a \n51: catalytic metalloproteinase domain followed by a disintegrin-like and a \n52: cysteine-rich domain. The impact of jararhagin on hemostasis has been \n53: extensively studied using in vitro and in vivo model systems as well as in \n54: clinical studies. Jararhagin-induced hemorrhage is the result of the degradation \n55: of sub-endothelial matrix proteins leading to the disruption of the blood vessel \n56: endothelium, with accompanying disturbances in platelet function. The \n57: versatility of jararhagin is further demonstrated by its direct action on von \n58: Willebrand factor, the degradation of fibrinogen, by its inhibition of platelet \n59: adhesion to collagen and by its inability to be affected by the plasma inhibitor \n60: alpha(2)-macroglobulin. Collagen-induced platelet aggregation is inhibited by \n61: jararhagin though the binding of the molecule to the alpha(2) subunit I domain \n62: of the platelet surface alpha(2)beta(1) integrin (collagen receptor). Jararhagin \n63: also cleaves the beta(1) subunit of the same integrin, inhibiting platelet \n64: interaction and ultimately causing impairment of signal transduction. The effect \n65: of jararhagin on cell systems other than platelets is evaluated; in fibroblasts, \n66: jararhagin functions as a collagen-mimetic substrate and, in endothelial cells, \n67: it causes apoptosis and indirectly inhibits cell proliferation by release of \n68: angiostatin-like compounds. Jararhagin induces a strong pro-inflammatory \n69: response characterized by intense leukocyte accumulation at the site of the \n70: injection. Although hemorrhage and edema are a response to the direct effect of \n71: jararhagin, jararhagin-induced inflammation and necrosis are dependent on \n72: macrophages and key pro-inflammatory cytokines or their receptors. Some data \n73: also indicate that the toxin possesses anti-tumorgenic properties. Methods for \n74: inhibiting jararhagin are reviewed; this encompasses the use of synthetic \n75: peptides to the isolation of naturally occurring mammalian peptides and the \n76: development of toxin-specific antibodies through DNA immunisation and monoclonal \n77: antibody technologies. The availability of jararhagin makes it an important tool \n78: for research into the mechanisms of action of similar toxins, for insights into \n79: cellular interactions and for clinical investigations into the treatment of \n80: envenomings from B. jararaca.\n81: \n82: DOI: 10.1016/j.toxicon.2005.02.013\n83: PMID: 15922770 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 83 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:15922770\ntitle: Jararhagin and its multiple effects on hemostasis.\nauthors:\n- Laing GD\n- Moura-da-Silva AM\njournal: Toxicon\nyear: '2005'\ndoi: 10.1016/j.toxicon.2005.02.013\nkeywords:\n- Animals\n- Antibodies/metabolism\n- Apoptosis/drug effects\n- Bothrops\n- Cell Adhesion/drug effects\n- Collagen/metabolism\n- \"Crotalid Venoms/metabolism, toxicity\"\n- \"Endothelium, Vascular/drug effects\"\n- Fibrinogen/metabolism\n- \"Hemostasis/drug effects, physiology\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_15922770.md","time":{"start":1778432671352,"end":1778432671356}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_084689fc13ca7c64016a00ba9f214481a1805d0cf8f9c6231c"}},"id":"prt_e12d8fe76001R8AJggm1X0o9vP","sessionID":"ses_1ed2e5abdffeV49GJQcR5nFb98","messageID":"msg_e12d8efa50011CqFZOZvkbZgrB"}}
