{"type":"text","timestamp":1778432696881,"sessionID":"ses_1ed2e5abdffeV49GJQcR5nFb98","part":{"id":"prt_e12d95b55001sxnZqmwZVCFnwR","messageID":"msg_e12d953d4001aTNA8T78Wl27EB","sessionID":"ses_1ed2e5abdffeV49GJQcR5nFb98","type":"text","text":"The closest existing pattern is the symbiont-mediated host-process logical pattern: `intersection_of: GO:0044003` plus `negatively_regulates_in_another_organism` the host process. Existing platelet-specific non-symbiont terms are obsolete, while the venom counterpart remains active with the same target process.","time":{"start":1778432695125,"end":1778432696880},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_044450500cef2dff016a00bab7156481a3986b2bee9ea213f9","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778432707687,"sessionID":"ses_1ed2e5abdffeV49GJQcR5nFb98","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_M11J4wqJTMm8WlPlPLX34RiV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: RESEARCH.md\n+# Research: symbiont-mediated suppression of host platelet aggregation\n+\n+## PMID:15045140 \"Extracellular fibrinogen binding protein, Efb, from Staphylococcus aureus binds to platelets and inhibits platelet aggregation.\"\n+\n+Shannon and Flock describe a secreted Staphylococcus aureus extracellular fibrinogen-binding protein (Efb) that binds platelets and acts as a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation. This supports a GO biological process term for suppression of host platelet aggregation by a symbiont-derived product.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15045140 \"S. aureus produces and secretes a protein, extracellular fibrinogen binding protein (Efb), which contributes to virulence in wound infection. We have shown here that Efb is a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15045140 \"The enhanced Efb-dependent fibrinogen binding to platelets is of a nature that does not promote aggregation of the platelets; instead it inhibits aggregation.\"\n+\n+## PMID:15922770 \"Jararhagin and its multiple effects on hemostasis.\"\n+\n+This reference was already used on obsolete general platelet aggregation-in-another-organism terms and supports the related venom-specific active term, but it concerns venom rather than symbiont-mediated host process perturbation. It was not used as the definition citation for the new symbiont term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15922770 \"Collagen-induced platelet aggregation is inhibited by jararhagin though the binding of the molecule to the alpha(2) subunit I domain of the platelet surface alpha(2)beta(1) integrin (collagen receptor).\"\n*** Add File: DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+# Design patterns: symbiont-mediated suppression of host platelet aggregation\n+\n+No DOSDP YAML pattern was found for symbiont-mediated perturbation terms in `src/design_patterns` or `src/patterns`. Existing GO precedent consistently uses the following logical pattern for suppression of a host process by a symbiont:\n+\n+```obo\n+intersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\n+intersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism <host process> ! <host process label>\n+```\n+\n+Relevant precedents:\n+\n+* `GO:0052170` symbiont-mediated suppression of host innate immune response\n+* `GO:0052562` symbiont-mediated suppression of host immune response\n+* `GO:0140411` symbiont-mediated suppression of host stress granule assembly\n+* `GO:0140321` symbiont-mediated suppression of host autophagy\n+\n+The requested term follows this pattern with target process `GO:0070527` platelet aggregation. This also parallels the active venom-specific term `GO:0044477` venom-mediated suppression of platelet aggregation, which uses `negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0070527`.\n+\n+The new term should not be asserted as a subtype of the obsolete `GO:0035893` suppression of platelet aggregation in another organism. It also should not be asserted under venom-mediated hemostasis terms because the requested interaction mode is symbiont-mediated, not venom-mediated.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,14 @@\n+# Research: symbiont-mediated suppression of host platelet aggregation\n+\n+## PMID:15045140 \"Extracellular fibrinogen binding protein, Efb, from Staphylococcus aureus binds to platelets and inhibits platelet aggregation.\"\n+\n+Shannon and Flock describe a secreted Staphylococcus aureus extracellular fibrinogen-binding protein (Efb) that binds platelets and acts as a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation. This supports a GO biological process term for suppression of host platelet aggregation by a symbiont-derived product.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15045140 \"S. aureus produces and secretes a protein, extracellular fibrinogen binding protein (Efb), which contributes to virulence in wound infection. We have shown here that Efb is a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15045140 \"The enhanced Efb-dependent fibrinogen binding to platelets is of a nature that does not promote aggregation of the platelets; instead it inhibits aggregation.\"\n+\n+## PMID:15922770 \"Jararhagin and its multiple effects on hemostasis.\"\n+\n+This reference was already used on obsolete general platelet aggregation-in-another-organism terms and supports the related venom-specific active term, but it concerns venom rather than symbiont-mediated host process perturbation. It was not used as the definition citation for the new symbiont term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15922770 \"Collagen-induced platelet aggregation is inhibited by jararhagin though the binding of the molecule to the alpha(2) subunit I domain of the platelet surface alpha(2)beta(1) integrin (collagen receptor).\"\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+# Design patterns: symbiont-mediated suppression of host platelet aggregation\n+\n+No DOSDP YAML pattern was found for symbiont-mediated perturbation terms in `src/design_patterns` or `src/patterns`. Existing GO precedent consistently uses the following logical pattern for suppression of a host process by a symbiont:\n+\n+```obo\n+intersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\n+intersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism <host process> ! <host process label>\n+```\n+\n+Relevant precedents:\n+\n+* `GO:0052170` symbiont-mediated suppression of host innate immune response\n+* `GO:0052562` symbiont-mediated suppression of host immune response\n+* `GO:0140411` symbiont-mediated suppression of host stress granule assembly\n+* `GO:0140321` symbiont-mediated suppression of host autophagy\n+\n+The requested term follows this pattern with target process `GO:0070527` platelet aggregation. This also parallels the active venom-specific term `GO:0044477` venom-mediated suppression of platelet aggregation, which uses `negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0070527`.\n+\n+The new term should not be asserted as a subtype of the obsolete `GO:0035893` suppression of platelet aggregation in another organism. It also should not be asserted under venom-mediated hemostasis terms because the requested interaction mode is symbiont-mediated, not venom-mediated.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","relativePath":"RESEARCH.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,14 @@\n+# Research: symbiont-mediated suppression of host platelet aggregation\n+\n+## PMID:15045140 \"Extracellular fibrinogen binding protein, Efb, from Staphylococcus aureus binds to platelets and inhibits platelet aggregation.\"\n+\n+Shannon and Flock describe a secreted Staphylococcus aureus extracellular fibrinogen-binding protein (Efb) that binds platelets and acts as a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation. This supports a GO biological process term for suppression of host platelet aggregation by a symbiont-derived product.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15045140 \"S. aureus produces and secretes a protein, extracellular fibrinogen binding protein (Efb), which contributes to virulence in wound infection. We have shown here that Efb is a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15045140 \"The enhanced Efb-dependent fibrinogen binding to platelets is of a nature that does not promote aggregation of the platelets; instead it inhibits aggregation.\"\n+\n+## PMID:15922770 \"Jararhagin and its multiple effects on hemostasis.\"\n+\n+This reference was already used on obsolete general platelet aggregation-in-another-organism terms and supports the related venom-specific active term, but it concerns venom rather than symbiont-mediated host process perturbation. It was not used as the definition citation for the new symbiont term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:15922770 \"Collagen-induced platelet aggregation is inhibited by jararhagin though the binding of the molecule to the alpha(2) subunit I domain of the platelet surface alpha(2)beta(1) integrin (collagen receptor).\"\n","additions":14,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","relativePath":"DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+# Design patterns: symbiont-mediated suppression of host platelet aggregation\n+\n+No DOSDP YAML pattern was found for symbiont-mediated perturbation terms in `src/design_patterns` or `src/patterns`. Existing GO precedent consistently uses the following logical pattern for suppression of a host process by a symbiont:\n+\n+```obo\n+intersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\n+intersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism <host process> ! <host process label>\n+```\n+\n+Relevant precedents:\n+\n+* `GO:0052170` symbiont-mediated suppression of host innate immune response\n+* `GO:0052562` symbiont-mediated suppression of host immune response\n+* `GO:0140411` symbiont-mediated suppression of host stress granule assembly\n+* `GO:0140321` symbiont-mediated suppression of host autophagy\n+\n+The requested term follows this pattern with target process `GO:0070527` platelet aggregation. This also parallels the active venom-specific term `GO:0044477` venom-mediated suppression of platelet aggregation, which uses `negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0070527`.\n+\n+The new term should not be asserted as a subtype of the obsolete `GO:0035893` suppression of platelet aggregation in another organism. It also should not be asserted under venom-mediated hemostasis terms because the requested interaction mode is symbiont-mediated, not venom-mediated.\n","additions":19,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","time":{"start":1778432707678,"end":1778432707684}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_044450500cef2dff016a00bab8d62881a386a137c6c15a29f4"}},"id":"prt_e12d962310010vJuCjEQ68ieEw","sessionID":"ses_1ed2e5abdffeV49GJQcR5nFb98","messageID":"msg_e12d953d4001aTNA8T78Wl27EB"}}
